## AWS Security Services as Common Controls

AWS offers a set of security services that, when enabled at the account or organization level, provide monitoring and protection that applies across all systems running in that environment — including OpenMRS. These are common controls in the NIST RMF sense: implemented once, inherited by multiple systems, maintained by a central provider.

---

### Amazon GuardDuty — Threat Detection

GuardDuty is AWS's managed threat detection service. It continuously analyzes data from multiple sources — CloudTrail API logs, VPC Flow Logs, DNS logs, and increasingly S3 access logs and EKS audit logs — using machine learning and threat intelligence to identify suspicious activity.

What makes GuardDuty particularly valuable as a common control is that it requires no agents to be installed and no complex configuration to get started. You enable it at the account level and it begins monitoring immediately. For OpenMRS, GuardDuty would detect things like:

- API calls from unusual geographic locations or IP addresses associated with known malicious actors
- Attempts to disable CloudTrail logging — a common attacker tactic to cover tracks
- EC2 instances communicating with known command-and-control infrastructure
- Unusual data transfer patterns from S3 buckets containing patient data
- Credential abuse — for example, an IAM role making API calls it has never made before

The limitation worth documenting: GuardDuty detects and alerts. It does not automatically respond or remediate. Someone needs to be monitoring the alerts and taking action when findings are generated. An organization that enables GuardDuty but never reviews the findings has spent money without gaining security.

---

### AWS CloudTrail — Audit Logging

CloudTrail records every API call made in an AWS account — who made it, from where, at what time, and what the result was. It is both a security monitoring tool and a compliance requirement — HIPAA's audit control requirements demand the kind of access trail that CloudTrail provides for the AWS infrastructure layer.

As a common control, CloudTrail enabled at the organization level covers all systems in the AWS environment simultaneously. For OpenMRS, CloudTrail captures:

- All console and API access to the AWS account
- Changes to security group rules — helping detect misconfiguration or unauthorized changes
- IAM changes — new users, modified permissions, deleted policies
- S3 bucket access — who accessed which objects and when
- RDS API calls — database instance modifications, snapshot creations

The limitation: CloudTrail captures AWS API activity, not application-level activity. It does not capture who logged into OpenMRS or which patient records they accessed. That application-level audit logging is a system-specific control that OpenMRS itself must provide — as I noted in the tailoring and common controls work from the past two days.

---

### AWS Config — Configuration Compliance Monitoring

AWS Config continuously evaluates the configuration of AWS resources against defined rules and alerts when something drifts from the approved baseline. For OpenMRS, relevant Config rules might include:

- Verify that RDS instances have encryption at rest enabled
- Confirm that S3 buckets do not have public access enabled
- Check that security groups do not allow unrestricted inbound access on sensitive ports
- Ensure CloudTrail is enabled and logging to a protected bucket
- Verify that MFA is enabled on all IAM user accounts

Config's value as a common control is that it provides continuous compliance verification rather than point-in-time assessment. Instead of discovering during an annual audit that an S3 bucket was misconfigured six months ago, Config alerts immediately when a configuration change creates a compliance gap. That shift from periodic to continuous is directly aligned with the RMF's continuous monitoring requirements.

The limitation: Config evaluates configurations — it does not test whether controls are actually effective. A security group rule might be technically compliant with a Config rule but still not provide adequate protection if the rule is written too broadly. Config is a necessary but not sufficient compliance tool.

---

### AWS Security Hub — Centralized Security Findings

Security Hub aggregates findings from GuardDuty, AWS Inspector, IAM Access Analyzer, AWS Config, and third-party security tools into a single dashboard. For an organization managing multiple systems in AWS — not just OpenMRS but billing systems, HR platforms, clinical tools — Security Hub provides the unified visibility that a GRC program needs.

For MyClinic specifically, Security Hub would allow the ISSO to see the security posture of all AWS-hosted systems in one place, prioritize findings by severity, track remediation progress, and demonstrate compliance status to the Authorizing Official without having to manually aggregate data from multiple sources.

The limitation: Security Hub is only as useful as the tools feeding into it. If GuardDuty is not enabled, or if Inspector is not running vulnerability assessments, Security Hub will have gaps in its picture. The value of centralization depends on the quality and completeness of the underlying sources.

