## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clicked most today is the relationship between AWS native security tools and the people and processes that make them useful.

GuardDuty, CloudTrail, Config, and Security Hub are genuinely powerful. Enabled together, they provide a level of visibility into the AWS environment that would be extremely difficult to replicate with on-premises infrastructure. But they all require someone to act on what they surface. A GuardDuty finding that goes unreviewed for two weeks is not a security control — it is a log entry. A Config alert about a misconfigured S3 bucket that nobody is assigned to remediate is not a compliance mechanism — it is documentation of an existing gap.

This connects directly back to the GRC roles from Day 22. The ISSO needs to be monitoring GuardDuty findings, reviewing Config compliance reports, and acting on Security Hub alerts. If the ISSO is stretched too thin — a common reality in small healthcare organizations — the tools exist but the program does not function. That is a people and resource problem that technology cannot solve.

