## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2019 Capital One breach** — which I covered briefly on Day 16, but want to revisit through the specific lens of detection tools.

Capital One had AWS GuardDuty enabled at the time of the breach. GuardDuty actually generated findings related to the attacker's activity — the exfiltration of data from S3 involved activity patterns that the tool was designed to detect. But the findings were not acted on quickly enough to prevent the breach. The attacker exfiltrated data over a period of time before the activity was investigated and the breach was confirmed.

That is not a criticism of GuardDuty — the tool did what it was supposed to do. It is a reminder that detection without response is incomplete. The Capital One breach led to significant improvements in how AWS native security tools are integrated with response processes — including the development of automated response playbooks that can trigger remediation actions in real time rather than waiting for human review.

For OpenMRS, the lesson is that enabling GuardDuty and CloudTrail is necessary but not sufficient. The security program needs defined processes for reviewing findings, prioritizing them, escalating them, and responding to them. Those processes are what transform a collection of security tools into a functioning security program.

