## Connecting Today's Work to the Risk Register

Looking back at the risk register from Day 25, today's AWS security tools directly address several of the registered risks:

| Risk Register Entry | Relevant AWS Tool | How It Helps |
|---|---|---|
| Ransomware attack (MYC-002) | GuardDuty | Detects C2 communication, unusual API calls, lateral movement indicators |
| Insider access/data misuse (MYC-005) | CloudTrail + Security Hub | Records all API activity; surfaces anomalous access patterns |
| HIPAA compliance failure (MYC-003) | AWS Config | Continuously verifies encryption, access control, and logging configurations |
| Third-party vendor failure (MYC-004) | CloudTrail + GuardDuty | Monitors vendor API activity; detects unusual access patterns from third-party credentials |
| System downtime (MYC-001) | AWS Config + CloudTrail | Detects configuration changes that could affect availability; supports incident investigation |

Making that connection explicit is useful because it shows that the security tools are not independent additions — they are direct implementations of the risk treatment decisions documented in the register. Each tool addresses specific risks that have been identified, assessed, and prioritized through the GRC process.

