## What I Am Still Thinking About

One thing I want to understand better is how small healthcare organizations make realistic decisions about which AWS security tools to prioritize when budget is limited.

GuardDuty, Config, CloudTrail, and Security Hub all carry costs — not enormous costs, but real ones that accumulate. For a small clinic running OpenMRS, the question is not "should we use all of these?" but "which ones provide the most value per dollar given our specific risk environment?"

My instinct is that CloudTrail is non-negotiable — the audit logging it provides is both a HIPAA compliance requirement and a foundational security capability that everything else depends on. GuardDuty is high value for the cost given the threat environment healthcare organizations face. Config provides continuous compliance verification that is worth the investment given the cost of misconfiguration-related breaches. Security Hub is most valuable when multiple other tools are already feeding into it — less so if you are only running one or two sources.

But I want to think through this more carefully with actual cost estimates as the project develops.

